rComments: Overall just a bad lecturer. She asked open ended questions looking for specific answers and if we needed time to think she accused us all of not doing the readings. She did not accept a drs note when I came down with the flu during midterms. Commenting in class was 10% of the grade but she only called on students that were going with her program.

I learned more with the tutor than in lecture/lab. Was struggling and went to her office hours and she was absolutely no help. The class size dwindled in part to the difficulty of the course but also due to her lackings as an instructor. Overall, she's not a very strong or effective teacher.

She's a pretty good lecturer, but sometimes can go off-topic. She really knows her Anthropology and is always willing to help students in need. The quizzes are really easy to get A's on as long as you make flashcards. The exams were pretty tough, but they were curved. Overall a pretty effective teacher and not too bad on the eyes either. ;)
Quizzes/labs/assignments were 55% of our total grade. No study guides for tests. She knows what shes talking about. Hard class though. She's a hard grader.

She's extremely helpful in office hours and wants her students to do well if they are willing to study. That said, SkeletalB io is not an easy course, it will be  diminish your social life--and if it doesn't, you won't be able to pass the weekly practicals. The class eventually got smaller, because students couldn't handle the heat.
Human Skeletal Biology is a very difficult course, and while Stephanie is very knowledgeable on the subject, she is not helpful and the quizzes consist of specimens that we never see in the lab.
super helpful and easy to approach
